article.description: Howard Eisley, promoted from third-stringer to backup, led the New York Knicks to their first victory since Feb. 13, a down-to-the-wire 89-87 victory Friday night over the Seattle SuperSonics.
article.headline: Knicks end their six-game slump
article.linkText: Knicks end Sonics' road winning streak at eight
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Howard Eisley finally got some meaningful playing time and performed well enough to expect more.
Eisley

After being promoted from third-stringer to backup, Eisley led the New York Knicks to their first win since Feb. 13, a down-to-the-wire 89-87 victory Friday night over the Seattle SuperSonics. Eisley had 14 points and eight assists and played the final 14½ minutes as the Knicks snapped a six-game losing streak and ended Seattle's road winning streak at eight games. "It's been very frustrating, a very frustrating season not only for me but for the team," said Eisley, who appeared in only 17 of New York's first 58 games. "I started to feel a lot more comfortable out on the floor as the game went on." Allan Houston scored 22 points, and Kurt Thomas had 14 points and 15 rebounds for the Knicks, who took control with an 18-4 run after Eisley entered late in the third quarter. New York nearly blew an eight-point lead in the final 30 seconds, but Gary Payton missed a 3-pointer at the buzzer that would have won it for Seattle. Rashard Lewis scored 22 points, Payton had 21 and Brent Barry had 17 points, a career-high 15 rebounds and seven assists for Seattle, which hadn't lost on the road since Jan. 23. Eisley sat out 41 of New York's first 58 games after being brought to New York in the Glen Rice trade along with his seven-year, $41 million contract. "I don't think any player comes into a situation thinking that, but the reality is it happened and there's nothing I can do about it now," said Eisley, who was buried behind Mark Jackson and Charlie Ward in the point guard rotation. Coach Don Chaney decided to try something different in light of the losing streak. "I'd rather see what Howard can do now than say at the end of the season 'I should have used Howard,"' Chaney said. Chaney complained before the game about how the Knicks seemed to be doing everything wrong in fourth quarters -- committing turnovers, taking poor shots and failing to move around on offense. Eisley changed all that, bringing a dose of energy that the Knicks have been missing all season. The Knicks trailed 62-55 when Eisley re-entered with 2:24 left in the third quarter, and he immediately started to make things happen. New York pulled within three by the end of the quarter, and Eisley hit a driving layup with 10:21 left in the fourth to give the Knicks their first lead of the second half, 65-64. Eisley scored four straight points to complete an 18-4 run, and after Barry hit a 3-pointer, Eisley assisted on consecutive buckets as New York took a 77-69 lead. Eisley then drew a double-team 20 feet from the basket and flung a crosscourt pass to Latrell Sprewell for a wide-open 3-pointer that gave New York an 80-70 lead. "We needed a win, and Howard did a great job and won the ballgame for us tonight," Jackson said. Seattle pulled within five before Eisley found Othella Harrington open underneath for a jump hook, and Shammond Williams fired up an airball from 3-point range with Eisley defending him. Eisley hit one of two free throws with 1:03 left for an 84-76 lead, then made a pair with 54 seconds left after Barry hit another 3-pointer. The Sonics pulled within three as Payton hit a 3 off a stolen inbounds pass, and Houston made just one of two free throws with 9.2 seconds left. Lewis hit a 3-pointer with 4.4 seconds left to make it 88-87, and the Sonics fouled Harrington with 3.7 remaining. Harrington, 1-for-4 from the line up to that point, missed the first and made the second. Payton then rushed upcourt and got off a 3-point shot that missed everything. "I was trying to look for everybody else, but I didn't get a look," Payton said. "I should have taken my time. It shouldn't have come down to that."

Game notes
The game was announced as the 421st consecutive sellout for the Knicks, but there were at least 1,000 empty seats. ... The Sonics have lost four straight at Madison Square Garden. ... Seattle dropped to 17-9 against teams from the East. They also had their overall four-game winning streak snapped. ... Seattle's team record for consecutive road victories is 10, set in 1994-95.
